The Shortcut
Dev had a gift for finding the easiest way to do anything, even when the easiest way took longer than just doing the thing.
He lived above a bakery that needed someone to sweep the floors each morning for a bit of extra cash. Dev took the job, then spent his first week engineering a broom-and-string contraption to sweep "automatically" while he stayed in bed. It took him four days to build, snapped on the fifth, and left more flour on the walls than the floor ever had. Sweeping by hand would have taken ten minutes.
"You spent more effort avoiding the effort," said Ana, who ran the bakery, staring at the wreckage of string and bristles.
"That's not laziness," Dev said. "That's optimization."
Ana didn't fire him. She just quietly moved the broom to a locked closet and gave him the key only at sweeping time, which meant he now had to walk downstairs twice a day instead of once. Dev complained about this for a week, entirely missing the irony.
Summer came, and with it a delivery order too big for Ana to handle alone. She asked Dev to help carry trays to the market square. He agreed, on the condition that he could use his cousin's wheelbarrow. Fair enough — except the wheelbarrow had a flat tire, and Dev spent the whole morning patching it with bakery dough instead of walking two blocks to the hardware store for a real patch. By the time he gave up and carried the trays by hand, the bread had gone cold and Ana had lost half her morning customers.
She didn't yell. She just handed him the schedule for the next day, and the day after, and the day after that, until "helping out sometimes" had quietly become "showing up every morning," because that was easier for her than trusting him to remember on his own.
Dev never did learn to love hard work. But somewhere between the broom and the wheelbarrow, he learned something almost as useful: that the fastest way through a job was usually just doing it, and that the effort he spent dodging chores would have finished most of them twice over.
He still took shortcuts. He just got better, eventually, at telling the clever ones from the ones that only felt clever.
